LOCAL PIPE LINE TARIFF CONTAINING RULES AND REGULATIONS GOVERNING THE TRANSPORTATION AND HANDLING OF PETROLEUM PRODUCTS TRANSPORTED BY PIPELINE The matter published herein will have no adverse effect on the quality of the human environment. ISSUED: January 4, 2017 EFFECTIVE: February 4, 2017 Issued by: [W] Fernando Luna Ignacio Arroyo President P.M.I. Services North America, Inc. 909 Fannin St., Suite 3200 Houston, TX 77010 Compiled by: Darryn Tollefson Vice President P.M.I. Letter suffixes will be used in alphabetical sequence starting with A. EXAMPLE - Item 60-A cancels Item 60; and Item 90-B cancels 90-A in a prior supplement, which, in turn, cancelled Item 90. ITEM 10 - METHOD OF DENOTING REISSUED MATTER IN SUPPLEMENTS Matter brought forward without change from one supplement to another will be designated as "Reissued" by a reference mark in the form of a square enclosing a number, the number being that of the supplement in which the reissued matter first appeared in its currently effective form. To determine the supplement's original effective date, refer to the explanation of reference marks in the supplement. For further details, consult the supplement in which the reissued matter first became effective. ITEM 15 - REFERENCE TO ITEMS, NOTES, RULES, ETC. When reference is made in this tariff, and supplements hereof, to items, notes, rules, etc., such references are continuous and include supplements to and successive reissues of such items, notes rules, etc. DEFINITIONS ITEM 20 - DEFINITIONS "API" means American Petroleum Institute. "ASTM" means American Society for Testing Materials. "Barrel" means Forty-two (42) gallons at sixty degrees (60 ) Fahrenheit and zero ("0") gauge pressure if the vapor pressure is at or below atmospheric pressure, or at equilibrium pressure if the vapor pressure of the petroleum is above atmospheric pressure. "Batch" refers to a volume of Petroleum Product moved through Carrier's system as an identified unit. "Carrier" means and refers to PMI Services North America, Inc. "Consignee" means and refers to the party, including a connecting pipeline, to whom Shipper has authorized the delivery of Petroleum Products. "Delivery" means the transfer of Petroleum Product from Carrier at destination to Consignee. "Destination" means the facility of Carrier at which Carrier delivers Petroleum Products out of Carrier's pipeline. "New Shipper" means a Shipper that is not a Regular Shipper. A Shipper that becomes a New Shipper shall remain one for twelve (12) consecutive calendar months. "Origin" means the facility of Carrier at which Carrier received Petroleum Products into Carrier's pipeline. "Petroleum Products" means the commodities more specifically defined in Item 25 and meeting the specifications referenced in Item 30. "Regular Shipper" means a Shipper that has shipped product on the Carrier's system each month within the 12-month period preceding the first day of a month in which the system or a portion of the system is prorationed. "Receipt" means the transfer from Shipper at Origin to Carrier for transportation. "Shipper" means the party who contracts with the Carrier for transportation of Petroleum Products pursuant to the terms of this tariff. "Tender" means an offer by a Shipper to Carrier of a stated quantity of Petroleum Products from a specified Origin to a specified Destination pursuant to the terms of this tariff. GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS COMMODITY DESCRIPTION AND MEASUREMENT ITEM 25 - PETROLEUM PRODUCTS DEFINED Where the term Petroleum Products is used, the same refers to: Unleaded Gasolines Petroleum Fuel Oil Distillates Commercial Jet Fuels ITEM 30 - PRODUCTS ACCEPTANCE SPECIFICATIONS Petroleum Products shall be accepted for transportation only when such Petroleum Products meet all required specifications as uniformly established by Carrier. All of the required specifications for Petroleum Products shall be issued from time to time in the manner and to the extent appropriate to facilitate the efficient and economical use of operation of the Carrier's facilities and to reasonably accommodate Shipper's needs for transportation. Carrier's typical Petroleum Products specifications may be found in the Carrier's document titled Petroleum Products Specification, which is available to Shippers upon request. Carrier reserves the right to accept Petroleum Products of different specifications provided it can safely handle and efficiently segregate such products so as to avoid contamination of other Shippers' inventory. Petroleum Products will be accepted for transportation at such time as Petroleum Products of same quality and specifications are being transported from Origin to Destination. All additives and inhibitors to be included in Shipper's Petroleum Products must first be approved by the Carrier before such Petroleum Products will be accepted for transportation. Carrier shall have no obligation to accept Petroleum Products if such products have: - Water or other impurities; - A color darker than No. 3 ASTM - A vapor pressure of more than 15 pounds absolute at 100 degrees Fahrenheit; - An API gravity of less than 25 degrees or more than 80 degrees at 60 degrees Fahrenheit; - A viscosity of more than 4.3 centistokes at 100 degrees Fahrenheit; - A temperature of more than 100 degrees Fahrenheit. Gasolines containing methanol or ethanol as blending components will not be accepted for shipment. Shippers must inform Carrier at the time Petroleum Products are scheduled for shipment on any gasoline shipments that contain oxygenates. These gasolines may, at Carrier's discretion, be shipped as separate Batches. Shippers shall be responsible for downstream notification to all Consignee's or other receiving parties of gasolines containing oxygenates. The Shipper will be liable for any contamination of other Petroleum Products in Carrier's custody, except for negligence of the Carrier, and will be required to indemnify and reimburse Carrier for all costs associated with such contamination. Carrier may require Shipper to provide buffer material to protect the quality of other Shipper's Petroleum Products. Petroleum Products containing blending components other than pure hydrocarbons or that pose a personal health hazard to Carrier's employees are not acceptable for transportation unless Shipper notifies Carrier of the identification and concentration of such components and has received Carrier's agreement to transport such blended Petroleum Products before they enter Carrier's system. Shipper must report type and percent by volume of all non-hydrocarbon blending components. Carrier reserves the right to refuse to accept any shipment of product that is: (1) not in compliance with state and federal regulations, (2) a health hazard, (3) incompatible with its transportation system, method of operation or transportation of other Petroleum Product. GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS COMMODITY DESCRIPTION AND MEASUREMENT ITEM 35 - VOLUME CORRECTIONS AND TENDER DEDUCTIONS SECTION A. In measuring the quantity of Petroleum Products received and delivered, correction shall be made from volume at actual or observed temperature to volume at sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit. Quantities shall be corrected as to temperature from observed temperature to 60 Fahrenheit basis by use of applicable API-ASTM volume correction factor tables. Full deduction will be made for all water and other impurities. The net balance, after applicable deduction, will be the quantity deliverable by Carrier and upon which transportation charges will be assessed. SECTION B. To the extent the Carrier experiences a gain or loss of Petroleum Product volume in any month due to its pipeline operations, each Shipper shall be responsible for such gain or loss, as determined by the Carrier, in the same proportion as its share of the total quantity of Petroleum Products transported by the Carrier over the prior twelve (12) months PRESHIPMENT REQUIREMENTS AND PROCEDURES ITEM 40 - COMMODITY Carrier is engaged in the transportation of Petroleum Products specified and described in Item 25 and therefore will not accept any other commodities for transportation. No Petroleum Products will be received for transportation except good merchantable Petroleum Products of substantially the same kind and quality as that being currently transported through the same facilities for other Shippers. Consignor and Shipper warrant to Carrier that any Petroleum Products tendered to Carrier conform with the specifications for such Petroleum Products and are merchantable. Petroleum Products of substantially different grade or quality will be transported only in such quantities and upon such terms and conditions as Carrier and Shipper may agree. ITEM 45 - TESTING AND MEASURING Prior to acceptance of Petroleum Products for transportation the Carrier may require from Shipper a certificate from a certified laboratory setting forth, in detail, the specifications of each shipment of Petroleum Products. Carrier will also make such test of the Petroleum Products as it may deem appropriate. All shipments tendered to Carrier for transportation shall be gauged or metered by a representative of Carrier prior to, or at the time of Receipt from the Shipper, but the Shipper or Consignee shall at all times have the privilege of being present or represented during the testing, gauging or metering. Carrier may require the Shipper to furnish certified laboratory reports showing the results of tests of the Petroleum Products offered for transportation. Carrier may also make such tests of the Petroleum Products as it deems necessary. ITEM 50 - SCHEDULING OF SHIPMENT Petroleum Products shall be accepted for transportation at such time as Petroleum Products of the same specification are currently being transported from point of Origin to the Destination in accordance with schedules of shipments and consignments to be issued from time to time to each Consignor by the Carrier. Such schedules may be modified from time to time in the manner and to the extent reasonably desirable to facilitate the efficient and economical use of operation of the Carrier's facilities and to reasonably accommodate Consignor's needs for transportation. Carrier shall not be obligated to accept Petroleum Products for transportation during any calendar month unless (1) the Shipper, on or before the fifteenth day of the preceding calendar month, nominates in writing the kind and quantity of Petroleum Products to be tendered with the Scheduler, P.M.I. Services North America, Inc., 909 Fannin St., Suite 3200, Houston, Texas 77010, and (2) due to the bi-directional capability of the pipeline system, the Carrier may require the Shipper to provide Petroleum Products necessary for purposes of line displacement. If Shipper fails to make its written nomination on or before the 15th day of the proceeding month, to the extent Carrier has idle capacity during the month, Carrier will attempt to handle the scheduling of these late nominated shipments in a manner to facilitate the efficient, economic use and operation of the Carrier's facilities and to reasonably accommodate Consignor's needs for transportation of product. GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS PRESHIPMENT REQUIREMENTS AND PROCEDURES ITEM 55 - PRORATION OF PIPELINE CAPACITY 1. Conditions which trigger prorationing When the total volume of the various commodities offered for shipment on Carrier's facilities, in accordance with the procedures for scheduling of shipments, is greater than can be transported within the period covered by such schedules, then commodities offered by each Shipper, including any new Shipper, for transportation will be transported in such quantities and at such times, to the limit of Carrier's normal operating capacity, so as to avoid unjust discrimination or undue preference among Shippers and the fulfill requirements of governmental agencies. 2. Division of capacity between Shipper classes Except as provided in paragraphs 7 and 9, prorationed capacity shall be divided between Regular Shippers as a class and New Shippers as a class. 3. Availability of capacity to Regular Shippers After the adjustment for New Shippers, as provided in paragraphs 5 and 6, all remaining capacity plus any pour-over capacity (as determined in accordance with paragraph 7) plus any unused allocated capacity as determined in accordance with paragraph 9 shall be available to Regular Shippers who have nominated volumes for that month. 4. Allocation to each Regular Shipper Each Regular Shipper shall be allocated a volume of the capacity available to all Regular Shippers that is equal to the lesser of (a) its nomination, or (b) a fraction, the numerator of which is the total shipments by that Shipper on Carrier system during the twelve (12) months preceding the first day of the month for which the Shipper's allocation is being calculated, and the denominator of which is the total shipments during such 12-month period by all Regular Shippers, multiplied by the total capacity available to all Regular Shippers during that month. 5. Availability of capacity to New Shipper Nor more than five (5) percent of the total available prorationed capacity of Carrier system or portion thereof shall be made available to New Shippers. 6. Allocation to each New Shipper Each New Shipper shall be allocated a volume of the capacity available to all New Shippers which is equal to five (5) percent of the total available prorationed capacity of Carrier system or portion thereof divided by the number of New Shippers who nominated volumes for shipment on the system or portion thereof during the month for which the allocation is being calculated. 7. Pour-over capacity Any amount of prorationed capacity which is available to New Shippers under the rules in paragraphs 5 and 6 but is not nominated by an eligible New Shipper shall be deemed "pour-over capacity" and shall be made available to Regular Shippers in accordance with the rules in paragraphs 3 and 4. 8. Basis for allocation: notification When prorationing of the capacity of Carrier system or portion thereof is in effect available capacity shall be allocated among eligible Shippers on a monthly basis. 9. Reallocation of unused allocated capacity If, during a month of prorationing, a Shipper fails to use all of its allocated capacity, such unused capacity shall be available to other Shippers, as follows: (a) Unused allocated capacity resulting from a Regular Shipper's failure to use all of its allocated capacity shall be reallocated among other Regular Shippers in accordance with the rules in paragraph 10. (b) Unused allocated capacity resulting from a New Shipper's failure to use all of its allocated capacity shall be reallocated among other New Shippers in accordance with the rules in paragraph 6. GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS PRESHIPMENT REQUIREMENTS AND PROCEDURES ITEM 55 - PRORATION OF PIPELINE CAPACITY (Continued) 10. Failure to use allocated capacity (a) Except as provided in subparagraph (b) of this paragraph, a Shipper that fails to use all of its allocated capacity during a month of prorationing shall have its allocation of capacity reduced in each subsequent month of prorationing until the total reductions equal the amount of the deficiency. The amount of any such reduction shall be treated as unused allocated capacity and shall be reallocated among other Shippers in accordance with the rules in paragraph 9. (b) Reduction of a Shipper's allocation for failure to use its allocated capacity during a prior month of prorationing may be waived, in whole or in part if Carrier determines, in its sole discretion, that the Shipper's failure to use all of some of its allocated capacity was due to factors beyond the Shipper's reasonable control. 11. Transfer of prorated capacity; use of affiliates Except as provided in paragraph 9, prorated volumes allocated to a Shipper may not be assigned, conveyed, loaned, transferred to, or used in any manner by another Shipper. However, a Shipper's allocation may be transferred as an incident of the bona fide sale of the Shipper's business or to a successor to the Shipper's business by the operation of law, such as an executor of trustee in bankruptcy. A Shipper may not use an affiliated or cooperating entity to obtain an increased allocation of prorationed capacity or, in the case of a Regular Shipper, seek New Shipper status in order to pool two or more allocations to the benefit of the Shipper. ITEM 60 - ACCEPTANCE FREE FROM LIENS AND CHARGES The Carrier shall have the right to reject any Petroleum Products when tendered for shipment which may be involved in litigation, the title of which may be in dispute, or which may be encumbered by lien or charge of any kind. Further, Carrier may require Shipper's proof of perfect and unencumbered title or a satisfactory indemnity bond. An offer of Petroleum Products for shipment shall be deemed a warranty of title by the party offering, but acceptance shall not be deemed a representation by the Carrier as to title. Delivery of Petroleum Products to the Consignee designated by the Shipper shall relieve Carrier of all liability as to custody or title. ITEM 65 - CORROSION INHIBITORS To the extent Petroleum Products do not comply with corrosion standards established in the Carrier's product specifications for the material tendered, Shipper may be required to inject oil-soluble corrosion inhibitor, approved by Carrier, in the Petroleum Products to be transported. ITEM 70 - FACILITIES REQUIRED AT ORIGIN AND DESTINATION SECTION A. The Carrier will not provide storage or other tankage facilities at points of Origin or at Destinations. Petroleum Products will be accepted for transportation only when Shipper has provided equipment and facilities capable of delivering such tenders at a pumping rate equal to Carrier's current pumping rate and when Shipper or Consignee has furnished evidence to the Carrier that the Shipper or Consignee has ascertained adequate facilities at Destination which are available for receipt of the shipment as is arrives without delay. SECTION B. In the event Shipper or Consignee fails to provide adequate facilities at the Destination for receipt as provided in Section A hereof, Carrier shall have the right to make whatever arrangements for disposition as are deemed appropriate to clear the Carrier's facilities, including the right of private sale for the best price reasonably obtainable. The Carrier may be a purchaser at such sale. Out of the proceeds of said sale, the Carrier shall pay itself all transportation and other applicable lawful charges and necessary expenses of the sale and the expenses of caring for and maintaining the Petroleum Products until disposed of and the balance be held for whomsoever may be lawfully entitled thereto. ITEM 75 - PAYMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND OTHER CHARGES Transportation charges will be assessed and collected by Carrier at the rates established by the Carrier at the time of Receipt on the basis of the quantity received at origin after making adjustments as provided for herein. The transportation and all other applicable lawful charges accruing on Petroleum Products accepted for transportation shall be paid before release of Petroleum Products from the custody of Carrier. If required, all such applicable charges shall be prepaid at point of Origin. Petroleum Products accepted for transportation shall be subject to a lien for all applicable current and antecedent lawful charges. GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS PRESHIPMENT REQUIREMENTS AND PROCEDURES ITEM 75 - PAYMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND OTHER CHARGES (Continued) If such charges are not paid by the due date stated on the invoice, Carrier shall have the right to assess finance charges on the entire past due balance (including principal and accumulated but unpaid finance charges) until paid in full at the rate equal to the prime rate of interest charged by Citibank N.A., New York, New York as of the due date plus two (2) percentage points or the maximum finance charge rate allowed by law, whichever is less. Carrier reserves the right to set-off any such charges against any monies owed to Shipper by Carrier or any Petroleum Products of Shipper in Carrier's custody. ITEM 80 - TAX REGISTRATION Shippers and Consignees shall be required to provide proof of registration with or tax exemption from the appropriated Federal and/or State tax authorities related to the collection and payment of fuels excise tax or other similar taxes, levies, or assessments. Failure of the Shipper and Consignee to do so shall not relieve the Shipper or Consignee from the obligation to pay any such tax, levy, or assessment. Any tax, levy, assessment, or other charge imposed by such authority against Carrier as the result of such failure shall be collected by Carrier under the provisions of Item 75. ITEM 85 - PIPEAGE CONTRACTS REQUIRED Separate pipeage contracts in accordance with this tariff and these regulations covering further details may be required of a Shipper before any duty to transport shall arise. Connections to Carrier pipeline(s) will only be considered if made by formal written notification to Carrier and all requests will be subject to the following standards and conditions. All connections will be subject to design requirements necessary to protect the safety, security, integrity and efficient operation of Carrier pipeline(s) in accordance with generally accepted industry standards. Acceptance of any request for connection will be subject to compliance with governmental regulations. TRANSPORTATION SERVICES AND RELATED REQUIREMENTS ITEM 90 - MINIMUM SHIPMENT A tender will be accepted only when the total quantity covered thereby equals or exceeds 25,000 Barrels of Petroleum Products, of the same specifications for transportation at one point of Origin from one Shipper. Carrier may aggregate tenders below the minimum batch size provided that in the Carriers opinion, such below minimum tenders would not impede the operation of the system or result in unacceptable degradation of the quality of the product delivered to other Shippers. ITEM 95 - MINIMUM DELIVERY AT DESTINATION Carrier will deliver all or part of any shipment of Petroleum Products at destinations named herein provided that the quantity of Petroleum Products of same specification delivered to one Consignee at any established destination is not less than 25,000 Barrels. Carrier may make deliveries of less than 25,000 barrels provided that in the Carriers opinion, such below minimum deliveries would not impede the operation of the system or result in unacceptable degradation of the quality of the product delivered to other Shippers. ITEM 100 - DIVERSION OR RECONSIGNMENT If no out-of-line or backhaul movement or interference with shipping sequence is required, diversion or reconsignment may be made without charge, provided notice is given not less than forty-eight (48) hours before scheduled arrival at original destination, subject to the rates, rules and regulations as provided in this tariff. ITEM 105 - APPLICATION OF RATES FROM OR TO INTERMEDIATE POINTS Shipments of Petroleum Products accepted for transportation from any Origin or to any Destination not named in any tariff making reference hereto, which Origin or Destination is directly intermediate to any Origin or Destination from or to which a rate applying though such unnamed point is published, the Carrier will apply, from or to such unnamed intermediate point, the rate published from or to the next more distant point specified in the tariff. GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS TRANSPORTATION SERVICES AND RELATED REQUIREMENTS ITEM 110 - IDENTITY OF SHIPMENT Because it is impracticable to maintain the identity of each shipment or consignment of Petroleum Products, substitution of barrelage, but not substitution of one kind of Petroleum Product for another by Carrier, shall be permitted. SPECIAL AND ANCILLARY SERVICES AND RELATED REQUIREMENTS ITEM 115 - CHARGES FOR SPILL COMPENSATION ACTS AND REGULATIONS In addition to the transportation charges and all other charges accruing on Petroleum Products accepted for transportation, a per barrel charge will be assessed and collected in the amount of any tax, fee or other charge levied against the Carrier in connection with such Petroleum Products pursuant to any Federal, State, or Local act or regulation which levies a tax, fee, or other charge on the receipt, delivery, transfer, or transportation of such Petroleum Products within their jurisdiction for the purpose of creating a fund for the prevention, containment, clean up, and/or removal of spills and/or reimbursement of persons sustaining such costs of losses there from. The amount of any such charge will be established in this tariff before it is assessed to the Shipper. ITEM 120 - COMMUNICATION FACILITIES Where this Carrier maintains private communication facilities, messages incident to shipment may be transmitted by Carrier for Shipper without extra charges. However, Carrier shall not be liable for non-delivery of messages, for error or delay in transmission, or for interruption of service. LIABILITY AND CLAIM SETTLEMENT ITEM 125 - DUTY OF CARRIER The Carrier shall transport and deliver at Destination, with reasonable diligence, the quantity of Petroleum Product accepted for transportation, less the appropriate tender deduction. In the event of non-delivery due to interface cuts or other operating losses in excess of the tender deduction, the Carrier shall have the right to satisfy any claim by product replacement or cash payment. Petroleum Products will be accepted for transportation upon the conditions that: (1) the Carrier may inject corrosion inhibitor compound in the product to be transported; (2) the Carrier while in possession thereof will use diligence to transport same to destinations with a minimum amount of contamination and that it shall be subject to such changes in gravity, quality or characteristics while in transit as may result from the mixture with other Petroleum Products. Carrier will not be liable for discoloration, contamination or deterioration of Petroleum Products transported hereunder. ITEM 130 - LIABILITY OF CARRIER The Carrier shall not be liable for any delay in transportation or loss of Petroleum Products caused by acts of God; storm, flood, extreme weather, fire, explosion; war, invasion, hostilities, rebellion, terrorism, insurrections, riots; strikes, picketing or other labor stoppages, whether of Carrier's employees or otherwise; electrical or electronic failure or malfunction; communications failure or malfunction; computer hardware and/or software failure, malfunction, or inaccuracy; breakage or accident to machinery or equipment; proration; temporary restraining orders, injunctions or compliance orders issues by courts or governmental agencies; seizure or destruction under quarantine or customs regulations, or confiscation by order of any government or public authority, or risks of contraband or illegal transportation or trade; or any cause not due to the direct negligence of Carrier. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained in this tariff, unless caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of the Carrier, the Carrier's liability, if any, shall not extend to any indirect, consequential, incidental, or punitive damages, or to any loss of profits or revenues incurred by such Shipper that may result from the transportation (and all services and procedures related thereto), regardless of whether such claim arises under or results from contract, tort, or strict liability. In the event of such loss, each owner shall bear the loss in the same proportion as its share of the total quantity of the kind of product involved in the loss in the custody of the Carrier at the time of such loss. Each Shipper or Consignee shall be entitled to receive only so much of its share remaining after its due proportion of the loss is deducted. The Consignees showing the apportionment of the loss among the Shippers or Consignees involved. GENERAL RULES AND REGULATIONS LIABILITY AND CLAIM SETTLEMENT ITEM 130 - LIABILITY OF CARRIER (Continued) Carrier shall compute the quantities of loss and shall prepare and submit a statement to the Shippers. Carrier will transport and deliver Petroleum Products with reasonable diligence and dispatch, but will not be liable for delays in transportation of Petroleum Products to a particular market. The Carrier shall not be liable for discoloration, contamination or deterioration of Petroleum Products transported unless such discoloration, contamination or deterioration results from the direct negligence of the Carrier. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained in this tariff, unless caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of the Carrier, the Carrier's liability, if any, shall not extend to any indirect, consequential, incidental, or punitive damages, or to any loss of profits or revenues incurred by such Shipper that may result from the transportation (and all services and procedures related thereto), regardless of whether such claim arises under or results from contract, tort, or strict liability. If damage to Petroleum Products results from any cause other than the direct negligence of the Carrier while the Carrier is in possession or control of such Petroleum Products, each Shipper's or Consignee's share of the damaged Petroleum Product shall be in the same proportion as its share of the total quantity of shipments involved and each such Shipper or Consignee shall be allocated only its proportionate share of damaged Petroleum Product. Shipper and Consignee shall protect, indemnify, defend and hold Carrier, its parent and affiliates harmless from and against all claims, losses, suits, liability, fines, penalties and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees and expenses) of any kind or character arising from or related to (1) negligent or willful acts or omissions on the part of Shipper or Consignee, its employees, agents or contractors, or (2) liability arising from the chemical characteristics of product(s), except to the extent such liability arises from Carrier's direct negligence. Product(s) in this Item refers to any individual product, as defined in this Tariff (in Item 25 - Petroleum Products Defined), or any combination thereof. ITEM 135 - CLAIMS: TIME FOR FILING Claim for any delay, damage to, or loss of Petroleum Products must be made in writing to the Carrier within nine (9) months after delivery from the Carrier's facilities of the shipment involved at the Destination to which such shipment was consigned, or in case of failure by Carrier to deliver, then within nine (9) months after the date upon which delivery would have reasonably been completed by Carrier. Such written claim, as aforesaid, shall be a condition precedent to any suit. Suit for any delay, damage to, or loss of Petroleum Products shall be instituted within two (2) years and one (1) day after notice in writing is given by the Carrier to the claimant that the Carrier has disallowed the claim or any part thereof specified in the notice. Claims or suits for delay, damage to, or loss of Petroleum Products not filed or instituted in accordance with the foregoing provisions will not be paid, and Carrier will not be liable. SHIPPER COMMITMENTS ITEM 140 - DURATION OF SHIPPER COMMITMENTS (VOLUME INCENTIVE) To qualify for volume incentive local rates under this tariff, Shipper must enter into a prior written commitment with Carrier. Shipper shall make a commitment to ship from the date of its first shipment and extending for a period of 15 years thereafter. The Shipper's commitment will become effective on the first day of the month following acceptance of such commitment by Carrier. ITEM 145 - MINIMUM MONTHLY QUANTITY (VOLUME INCENTIVE) To qualify for volume incentive local rates under this tariff, Shipper shall, in addition to commitments indicated in Item 140, transport each month a volume of Petroleum Products not less than 5,000 Barrels times the number of days in such month, such monthly quantity, herein referred to as (the "Minimum Monthly Quantity"). In the event that, during any calendar month, Shipper transports less volume than the Minimum Monthly Quantity, such difference between the Minimum Monthly Quantity and the volume actually transported in any month, a "Deficiency Quantity", then, in addition to paying the applicable tariff for the volume of Petroleum Products actually transported during such month, Shipper shall also be obligated to pay the currently applicable tariff applied to the Deficiency Quantity, (a "Deficiency Payment"). The applicable tariff for determining the Deficiency Payment for such month shall be the then currently effective rate otherwise applied for local movements originating at Transmontaigne Terminal Facilities in Cameron County, TX and delivered at United States Mexico International Border. This rate is currently found in Item No. 100 of PMI FERC No. 8.2.0 as such may be amended or supplemented from time-to-time. ITEM 150 - CREDITS FOR EXCESS VOLUME (VOLUME INCENTIVE) If, in any month during the commitment indicated in Item 140, Shipper shall transport, or cause to be transported, volumes in excess of i) 10,000 Barrels times the number of days in such month, or ii) such greater Incentive Volume as defined in Item 155 hereof (the transportation of volume in excess of 10,000 Barrels or the Incentive Volume, as applicable, times the number of days in a certain month, an "Excess Volume"), then Shipper shall be given a future credit for the payment of transportation services in respect of such Excess Volume which will equal such Excess Volume times the applicable tariff, as such may be adjusted subject to provisions of Item 155, which may be applied exclusively to offset future Deficiency Payments, if any, which become outstanding, it being understood that Shipper shall pay Carrier for transportation services applicable under the tariff for such Excess Volume for the month the transportation service is provided. ITEM 155 - VOLUME INCENTIVE TARIFF (VOLUME INCENTIVE) If at any time during the commitment period indicated in Item 140, Carrier transports for the account of Shipper a minimum of 12,000 Barrels times the number of days during a period not less than 18 consecutive calendar months (an "Incentive Volume"), then Carrier agrees to transport such Petroleum Products applying the applicable volume incentive local rate indicated in Item No. 110 of PMI FERC No. 8.2.0, as such may be amended or supplemented from time-to-time, it being understood that for any month during such qualifying 18 consecutive calendar month or longer period, invoices for volume transported will be based on the effective non-volume incentive local rate currently published in PMI FERC No. 8.2.0, Item 100, except that an adjustment in respect of any applicable volume incentive local rate in FERC No. 8.2.0, Item 110, shall be reflected in the invoice for volume transported in a) the final month of any 18 consecutive calendar month period for which a volume incentive local rate applies, and in b) any consecutive month to follow for which a volume incentive local rate applies. To the extent volume transported by Shipper in any calendar month is less than the Minimum Monthly Quantity, such Deficiency Quantity may be included as part of the volume in the determination of whether a volume incentive local rate applies, provided that a Deficiency Payment has been made to Carrier or a credit from Excess Volume has been applied by Carrier in respect of such Deficiency Quantity. During any month in which Pipeline capacity is prorated among Shippers the Minimum Monthly Quantity as defined by Item No. 145 of this tariff will be reduced by the same factor by which a given Shippers capacity is reduced. FROM ORIGIN TO DESTINATION BASE RATE INCENTIVE RATE 100 PMIS's Terminal Facilities El Paso County, TX United States - Mexico International Border Near El Paso, TX [I] 507.13 [I] 67.87 200 Volume Incentive Program 1. Rates set forth in Item 100 apply to deliveries of Petroleum Products from the Origin defined as PMIS's Terminal Facilities in El Paso, TX to the Destination defined as the United States - Mexico International Border Near El Paso, Texas. Any Shipper desiring to ship volumes from the Origin to the Destination shall pay the Base Rate, unless it satisfies the conditions stated below in order to ship as a Participating Shipper at the Incentive Rate. Any Shipper desiring to avail itself of the Incentive Rate, as set forth herein must satisfy all of the following provisions to be a "Participating Shipper": * Shipper must enter into a prior written Throughput and Deficiency Agreement ("T&D") with Carrier with an Effective Date on or before January 31, 2011. The Commitment Term shall be at least one hundred fifty (150) months, but not longer than the effectiveness of this Item or any successive issues, reissues, amendments thereto, or extensions as provided for in the T&D. The initial commitment will be fifty (50) Contract Quarters, defined as fifty (50) consecutive three (3) calendar month periods where the first Contract Quarter begins on the Effective Date. * The Quarterly Guaranteed Committed Volume shall be equal to the amounts specified in Paragraph 3 of this Item. 2. In addition to the terms and conditions contained in this item, all applicable rules and regulations in PMI Services North America Inc.'s F.E.R.C. NO. 1, supplements thereto and reissues thereof, shall apply to Shippers and Participating Shippers. 3. The Quarterly Guaranteed Committed Volume under this Item shall be not less than the product of (i) 20,000 barrels per day multiplied by (ii) the number of days in such Contract Quarter, for each of the fifty (50) quarters in the Commitment Term ("the Quarterly Commitment"). 4. Carrier shall comply with 18 CFR 342.3 and 342.4 (a) in respect of making adjustments to the Base Rate, as such may be supplemented from time to time during the Commitment Term. Carrier may increase the Incentive Rate by the same percentage change as the change in the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers since the latter of either the Effective Date or the immediately prior change in the Incentive Rate; provided however that the Incentive Rate shall be no more than 44.21% of the Base Rate at any time. 5. Volumes delivered at the Destination for a Participating Shipper will apply toward the Quarterly Guaranteed Committed Volume. The Incentive Rate contained herein will only apply to volumes transported by the Participating Shipper, in its name, from Origin and delivered to the Destination from Shipper's inventory during the Commitment Term (i.e., the original shipment date must be within the Commitment Term) from the defined Incentive Rate Origin. 6. Carrier will invoice all Shippers at the rates set out in Paragraph 4 of this item, at the time of shipment. Shipper will bear all other applicable charges in PMI Services North America, Inc.'s F.E.R.C. No. 1 and any, supplements thereto and reissues thereof. 7. If at the end of any Contract Quarter, a Participating Shipper has not met the defined Quarterly Guaranteed Committed Volume threshold, as stated in Paragraph 3 of this item, the Participating Shipper will pay a deficiency equal to the difference between the defined Quarterly Guaranteed Committed Volume and the actual volume delivered during the applicable Contract Quarter multiplied by the Incentive Rate defined in Paragraph 4 of this item. In the event that such a "Deficiency Payment" occurs, the Participating Shipper will be credited for prepaid transportation, on a dollar for dollar basis, toward the Participating Shipper's payment obligations for its shipments of product volume applicable to this item during the remainder of the term of the T&D. Such prepaid transportation credits will not count towards the Quarterly Volume Commitment for the Contract Quarter in which they are used. At the expiration of the Commitment Term, the Participating Shipper shall have the immediately-following thirty six month period to apply any remaining Prepaid Transportation as a credit against the applicable transportation movement. All remaining Prepaid Transportation that is not applied within the allotted time period shall become sole property of PMI Services North America, Inc. 8. If a Participating Shipper fails to meet the applicable Quarterly Commitment and that failure is the direct result of the Carrier's inability to provide timely service, the applicable Quarterly Commitment shall be reduced pro rata on a day for day basis for each day that the Carrier was unable to provide timely service. The Participating Shipper must assert its claim of Carrier's failure to provide timely service in writing to Carrier within ten (10) days following the end of the calendar month during which Carrier did not provide timely service. The Participating Shipper will bear the burden of proof in showing that Carrier's failure to provide timely service did, in fact, result in the Participating Shipper's failure to meet its commitment obligation. 9. In the event a Shipper experiences Force Majeure that delays delivery of product to Carrier at point of origin, Carrier may, at its reasonable and non-discriminatory discretion, upon written notification of circumstances from Shipper, extend the Commitment Term. Such extension period shall in no event, individually or cumulatively, exceed a total of (90) days over the Commitment Term. Force Majeure shall mean any cause, event or circumstance of whatever nature which is not within the reasonable control of the Party claiming to be adversely affected thereby such as, but not limited to, acts of God, or public enemy, strikes, lockouts, or other industrial disturbances, wars, insurrections, riots or explosions.
